<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-298-314  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 298 314.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  May 28 1989 v138 n47,884 pF2(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Forget HDTV, it's already outmoded. (high definition television)(Business) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gilder, George.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The world verges on a technological transformation that willrender current television obsolete.andP;  Coming is the 'telecomputer,'which combines video and digital technologies with fiber optictransmission links.andP;  Unlike broadcast television, digital computertechnology is interactive.andP;  Viewers can participate in programs orcontrol what they see.andP;  Fiber optic networks, which are underdevelopment by Bell regional telephone companies, will carryamounts of information necessary for such systems.andP;  An obstacle totelecomputing is a coalition of interests converging on Congressin support of high-definition television (HDTV).andP;  Vital resourcesand political efforts are being diverted from the drive to replacebroadcasting with digital fiber networks.andP;  Congress should endregulatory constraints that prevent telephone companies fromconnecting fiber optics to the home.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     High-Definition TelevisionTelevisionFuture TechnologiesFuture of ComputingFiber OpticsInteractive SystemsDigital CommunicationsTelephone CompaniesBell Regional Holding CompaniesForeign CompetitionTelecommunicationsGovernment RegulationSocial IssuesUnited States. Congress.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>